  "prompt": "I have a blue yeti microphone, but it picks up so much background noise even tho I got a stand. Someone please help me, or recommend me another mic :)",
  "response": "The Blue Yeti is a great microphone, but its sensitivity and omnidirectional pickup pattern can make it prone to picking up background noise, especially in untreated environments. Here are some tips to reduce background noise with your Blue Yeti, as well as recommendations for alternative microphones if needed:\n\n---\n\n### **Tips to Reduce Background Noise with Your Blue Yeti**\n1. **Switch the Polar Pattern**  \n   - The Blue Yeti has multiple polar pattern settings. Use the **cardioid pattern** (the heart-shaped icon) to focus on sound directly in front of the mic and reduce noise from the sides or rear.\n\n2. **Adjust the Gain**  \n   - Lower the gain on the microphone to reduce sensitivity to background noise. You can amplify the signal later in software if needed.\n\n3. **Use a Pop Filter**  \n   - A pop filter can help reduce plosive sounds and improve clarity, making it easier to distinguish your voice from background noise.\n\n4. **Position the Mic Correctly**  \n   - Keep the microphone close to your mouth (about 6-8 inches away) and ensure it\u2019s facing you directly. This helps your voice dominate the signal.\n\n5. **Use Noise Suppression Software**  \n   - Software like **Krisp**, **RTX Voice** (NVIDIA), or **NVIDIA Broadcast** can effectively remove background noise in real-time.\n\n6. **Improve Your Recording Environment**  \n   - Add **acoustic treatment** (e.g., foam panels) to reduce echoes and background noise. Alternatively, record in a quieter, carpeted room.\n\n7. **Use a Shock Mount**  \n   - A shock mount can reduce vibrations and desk noise that the microphone picks up.\n\n8. **Experiment with Mic Placement**  \n   - Place the microphone on a separate stand or arm away from your desk to avoid picking up keyboard or mouse sounds.\n\n---\n\n### **Alternative Microphones with Better Noise Rejection**\nIf you\u2019re still struggling with background noise, here are some microphones that are known for better noise rejection:\n\n1. **Dynamic Microphones**  \n   Dynamic mics are less sensitive to background noise compared to condensers like the Blue Yeti.  \n   - **Shure SM58** (classic dynamic mic, great for voice).  \n   - **Shure MV7** (USB/XLR hybrid, excellent for podcasting and streaming).  \n   - **Rode PodMic** (perfect for podcasting and voice-over work).  \n\n2. **Hypercardioid or Supercardioid Microphones**  \n   These have narrower pickup patterns, focusing on your voice while rejecting noise from the sides and rear.  \n   - **Audio-Technica AT2020** (cardioid condenser, affordable and clean sound).  \n   - **Rode NT-USB Mini** (compact USB mic with good noise rejection).  \n\n3. **Lavalier Microphones**  \n   Lav mics are great for close-up voice recording and minimizing background noise.  \n   - **Rode SmartLav+** (clip-on lav mic for clear voice capture).  \n\n4. **Streaming/Content Creation Mics**  \n   - **Elgato Wave:3** (comes with software for noise suppression and mixing).  \n   - **Razer Seiren Mini** (compact, affordable, and good for streaming).  \n\n---\n\n### **Final Thoughts**\nIf you\u2019re happy with the Blue Yeti, try optimizing its setup first (e.g., using noise suppression software, adjusting gain, and improving your environment). If background noise is still a major issue, consider switching to a dynamic microphone or one with better noise rejection. Let me know if you need more help!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
